  <article class="py-16 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 prose prose-lg">
      <p>Florida's hot, humid climate is tough on garage doors. The combination of heat, moisture, and salt air (for coastal areas) can accelerate wear and tear on every component of your garage door system. Regular maintenance helps prevent unexpected breakdowns and extends the life of your door. Here are five essential tips from the experts at <a href="/" class="text-accent hover:underline">ASAP Zephyrhills Garage Door Repair</a>.</p>

      <h2 class="font-heading text-3xl tracking-wide text-primary mt-10 mb-4">1. Lubricate Moving Parts Every 6 Months</h2>
      <p>Florida's humidity can cause metal parts to corrode faster than in drier climates. Apply a silicone-based lubricant to the springs, hinges, rollers, and tracks every six months. Avoid using WD-40 as a lubricant; it is a solvent that can actually strip away grease. Proper lubrication reduces friction, prevents rust, and keeps your door operating quietly.</p>

      <h2 class="font-heading text-3xl tracking-wide text-primary mt-10 mb-4">2. Inspect and Replace Weatherstripping</h2>
      <p>The rubber weatherstripping along the bottom of your garage door takes a beating from Florida's sun and rain. Cracked or worn weatherstripping allows water, insects, and debris into your garage. Check the seal every few months and replace it when you notice cracks, gaps, or hardening. This simple fix helps keep your garage clean and dry.</p>

      <h2 class="font-heading text-3xl tracking-wide text-primary mt-10 mb-4">3. Test the Auto-Reverse Safety Feature Monthly</h2>
      <p>Your <a href="/services/garage-door-opener-repair" class="text-accent hover:underline">garage door opener</a> should have an auto-reverse feature that stops and reverses the door if it contacts an object. Test this monthly by placing a piece of wood or a roll of paper towels in the door's path. If the door does not reverse upon contact, call a professional immediately. This safety feature protects your family, pets, and vehicles.</p>

      <h2 class="font-heading text-3xl tracking-wide text-primary mt-10 mb-4">4. Check Springs and Cables for Wear</h2>
      <p>Garage door <a href="/services/garage-door-spring-repair" class="text-accent hover:underline">springs and cables</a> are under tremendous tension and can be dangerous if they fail. Visually inspect them for signs of rust, fraying, or stretching. Never attempt to repair or adjust springs yourself, as this can cause serious injury. If you notice any damage, contact a professional <a href="/services/garage-door-spring-repair" class="text-accent hover:underline">spring repair service</a> right away.</p>

      <h2 class="font-heading text-3xl tracking-wide text-primary mt-10 mb-4">5. Keep Tracks Clean and Aligned</h2>
      <p>Dirt, leaves, and debris can accumulate in the tracks and cause your garage door to operate poorly or go off track. Wipe down the tracks with a damp cloth regularly and check that they are properly aligned. Misaligned tracks put extra stress on the opener and can lead to premature wear on rollers and other components.</p>

